
## How to search for papers
•	Use Google Scholar
o	Searching with keywords always helps
	Get new papers of your field of research Set alerts using the key words.
•	Use Arxiv (does not apply to all students)
o	Not all areas of research use this, but mostly CS, Physics researchers upload unpublished papers on Arxiv.
o	Those who are doing ML research may find Arxiv useful.
  
## Referencing software
Referencing software is not only useful for citing papers for academic writings, but also useful for gathering & categorizing the papers you read.
1. Mendeley
•	Key Features:
o	Reference management and citation generation.
o	PDF reader with annotation tools.
o	Collaboration tools for sharing references and research papers.
o	Integration with Microsoft Word for citation insertion.
o	Web importer for easily adding references from databases and websites.
o	Free storage for up to 2GB of PDFs and references.
•	Strengths:
o	User-friendly interface.
o	Strong community and collaboration features.
o	Good PDF annotation tools.
o	Cross-platform availability (Windows, Mac, Linux, iOS, Android).
•	Weaknesses:
o	Limited storage in the free version.
o	Some advanced features require a paid subscription.
o	Less customizable compared to some other tools.
o	Subscription-based payment
	5GB: $4.99/month or $55/yr
	10GB: $9.99/month or $110/yr
	100GB: $14.99/month or $165/yr
2. EndNote
•	Key Features:
o	Comprehensive reference management and bibliography creation.
o	Extensive library of citation styles.
o	Integration with major word processors for citation insertion.
o	PDF import and management.
o	Advanced search and organization features.
o	Cloud sync and sharing options.
•	Strengths:
o	Highly customizable and flexible.
o	Robust library and citation style management.
o	Strong support for complex referencing needs.
o	One-time payment for usage
	$150 for student license
•	Weaknesses:
o	Higher cost compared to other tools.
o	Steeper learning curve.
o	Less focus on collaborative features.
3. Zotero
•	Key Features:
o	Reference management and citation generation.
o	Web browser integration for easy reference capture.
o	PDF annotation tools.
o	Integration with Microsoft Word, Google Docs.
o	Free storage for up to 300MB, with paid options for more storage.
o	Strong support for various citation styles and formats.
•	Strengths:
o	Open-source and free to use.
o	Excellent web browser integration.
o	Strong community support and add-ons.
o	Good collaborative features.
•	Weaknesses:
o	Limited storage in the free version.
o	User interface can be less intuitive for new users.
o	Subscription-based payment
	2GB: $20/yr
	6GB: $60/yr
	Unlimited: $120/yr
4. RefWorks
•	Key Features:
o	Reference management and citation generation.
o	Integration with major word processors.
o	PDF management and annotation.
o	Cloud-based storage and access.
o	Collaboration tools for sharing references and documents.
o	Advanced search and organization features.
•	Strengths:
o	Cloud-based with easy access from anywhere.
o	Good support for collaboration.
o	Integration with various academic databases.
•	Weaknesses:
o	Subscription-based with no free version. (Quotation-based pricing)
o	Can be less intuitive for beginners.
o	Limited customization options.
5. Papers
•	Key Features:
o	Reference management and citation generation.
o	PDF reader with annotation tools.
o	Integration with Microsoft Word for citation insertion.
o	Cloud storage and synchronization across devices.
o	Advanced search and organizational tools.
•	Strengths:
o	User-friendly interface.
o	Strong PDF management and annotation features.
o	Good synchronization across multiple devices.
•	Weaknesses:
o	Subscription-based with no free version.
	$3/month for students (Billed annually)
o	Less focus on collaboration features.
o	Limited citation style options compared to some other tools.
6. Citavi
•	Key Features:
o	Reference management and citation generation.
o	Knowledge organization with task planning and project management tools.
o	Integration with Microsoft Word for citation insertion.
o	PDF management and annotation.
o	Cloud synchronization and collaboration features.
•	Strengths:
o	Comprehensive project management features.
o	Strong support for organizing research notes and tasks.
o	Good collaborative features.
•	Weaknesses:
o	Higher cost, particularly for the cloud version.
	Windows+Web version: $89/yr, Windows desktop version: $329 (one-time purchase)
o	Steeper learning curve.
o	Less focus on ease of use compared to some other tools.

Recommendation: 
•	Start with free trial versions and find the best fit for you. 
•	My (Soonwook Kim) preference is Endnote, which is decent for categorizing & saving papers and also convenient referencing during paper writings. Considering the price option, Endnote is the cheapest option with excellent capabilities.
